{"plan_objective_id": 2, "updated_plan_objective_json": "{
  "id": 2,
  "objective": "Research design-as-code / programmatic frameworks (atopile, tscircuit, SKiDL, Horizon EDA, KiCad Python/IPC API, PCBmodE)",
  "rationale": "Part (b) needs coverage of programmatic frameworks and their automation level",
  "status": "completed",
  "result": "Gathered evidence on: BHDL (Racket eDSL, auto-placement via RePlace+SA, exports KiCad PCB, BOM, open source); Polymorphic Blocks (Python HDL, generates netlists with footprints, exports to KiCad, interactive GUI); SKiDL (Python, generates KiCad netlists/schematics, used as backend by PCBSchemaGen/SchGen/pcbGPT); PCBSchemaGen (LLM->SKiDL->KiCad pipeline); pcbGPT (custom Python DSL->KiCad project). atopile and tscircuit known from domain knowledge as newer tools. KiCad Python API / kicad-cli known from documentation.",
  "evaluation": "Sufficient evidence from retrieved papers. Additional tools (atopile, tscircuit, PCBmodE) will be covered from domain knowledge as they lack peer-reviewed papers but are open-source projects."
}"}

{"plan_objective_id": 3, "updated_plan_objective_json": "{
  "id": 3,
  "objective": "Research recent (2020-2025) peer-reviewed/arXiv papers on automatic netlist/topology to placement/floorplan/board outline",
  "rationale": "Part (c) requires 8-15 recent papers on ML/RL placement, LLM-driven schematic-to-layout, constructive floorplanning, etc.",
  "status": "completed",
  "result": "Found and gathered evidence from 12+ relevant papers: (1) HiePlace (Li 2025, TCAD) - hierarchical MP-based PCB placement, 66% cost reduction, 7.7x speedup vs baselines; (2) Vassallo & Bajada (DATE 2024) - RL placement with TD3/SAC, 17-21% wirelength reduction; (3) Vashisht et al. (2020) - cyclic RL+SA placement; (4) Wang et al. (2024) - DRL+GNN chip floorplanning, 31.4% HPWL reduction on ISPD2005; (5) Li et al. (2025) - double-layer PCB placement algorithm; (6) Lim (2025) - component-centric DRL placement; (7) Basso (2026) - RL+R-GCN analog layout, 67.3% time reduction; (8) PCBSchemaGen (Zou 2025) - LLM->SKiDL->KiCad; (9) pcbGPT (King 2026) - NL->KiCad schematics, pass@1=0.90; (10) SchGen (Luo 2025) - finetuned LLM for schematic gen, 82% valid rate; (11) HWE-Bench (Qiu 2025) - 300 board-level tasks, best model 8.15% overall correct; (12) PCB-Bench (Li 2026) - multimodal LLM benchmark; (13) AMSnet-KG (Shi 2025) - KG-RAG for AMS design; (14) Krishnamoorthy (2025) - generative AI for platform HW design.",
  "evaluation": "14 papers identified covering the full spectrum from RL/ML placement to LLM-driven schematic generation to benchmarks. This exceeds the 8-15 paper target."
}"}

{"plan_objective_id": 4, "updated_plan_objective_json": "{
  "id": 4,
  "objective": "Assess the gap for a mixed-signal motor+sensor control board - how automatable is the intermediate step today, what requires human input, which tools work headlessly in CI",
  "rationale": "Part (d) requires an honest assessment specific to a mixed-signal MCU board with stepper drivers, solenoids, servos, HX711, etc.",
  "status": "completed",
  "result": "Based on all gathered evidence: HWE-Bench shows best LLM achieves only 8.15% full correct rate on board-level design tasks. pcbGPT achieves 0.90 pass@1 on schematic drafts but explicitly does NOT handle placement/routing/manufacturing. SchGen achieves 82% valid circuit rate but 60.5% functional correctness. For the specific mixed-signal motor/sensor board, the gap analysis: (1) Schematic capture is partially automatable via SKiDL/pcbGPT but requires human review for power/analog sections; (2) Component selection for stepper drivers, solenoids, HX711 requires domain expertise and datasheet reading; (3) Board outline and floorplan are not automated by any tool; (4) Headless/CI tools: SKiDL + KiCad CLI + atopile are the most scriptable; (5) Quilter/DeepPCB need a complete KiCad project as input, which none of the AI tools reliably produce end-to-end today.",
  "evaluation": "Assessment synthesized from HWE-Bench, pcbGPT, SchGen, PCBSchemaGen results and domain knowledge of the specific board requirements."
}"}

